  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7_6",
    "text": "Conclusions",
    "canon_role": "section_header",
    "bbox": [
      0.23203285832829343,
      0.6671511629231125,
      0.33059548039860587,
      0.6773255811757244
    ],
    "page": "docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7",
    "order": 24
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7_7",
    "text": "The matrix photochemistry of methyl thiofluoroformate, FC(O)SCH, follows closely the precedents set by the corresponding thiochloroformate, CIC(O)SCH39 The various reaction channels have been charted by characterization of the photoproducts by their IR spectra and by monitoring the behavior of the IR absorptions as a function of photolysis time. The conclusions have been endorsed by studying the effects of perdeuteration of the parent compound and carrying out quantum chemical calculations on the putative products.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.07790739298499909,
      0.6961805557569112,
      0.48665297089869763,
      0.8328488369494965
    ],
    "page": "docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7",
    "order": 25
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7_11",
    "text": "Scheme 2. Outline of the photochemical reactions of FC(O)SCH, isolated in a solid Ar matrix.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5112936388583573,
      0.7296511628375357,
      0.9219712370551556,
      0.7544642855107077
    ],
    "page": "docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7",
    "order": 26
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7_25",
    "text": "Experimental and Computational Procedures",
    "canon_role": "section_header",
    "bbox": [
      0.537987672839327,
      0.7703373019900128,
      0.8993839858875727,
      0.7877906971750293
    ],
    "page": "docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7",
    "order": 27
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7_26",
    "text": "FC(O)SCH, was prepared by the reaction of CIC(O)SCH, with TIF (both from Aldrich) at ambient temperature!\" and subsequently purified by repeated trap-to-trap condensation under vacuum. The purity of the compound was checked by reference to the IR spectrum of the vapor and to the 'H, 13C, and 19F NMR spectra of the liquid 8l The perdeuterated compound FC(O)SCD; was prepared for the first time by the corre-",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5112936378013916,
      0.7993551589555181,
      0.9240246290979927,
      0.8764880953537738
    ],
    "page": "docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7",
    "order": 28
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-chem.200700118.pdf_7_8",
    "text": "The photolytic interconversion of the two rotamers of FC(O)SCH is the first process observed on broadband UVvisible irradiation of the matrix-isolated molecule, behavior made familiar by analogous studies of other sulfenyl carbonyl compounds, for example, CIC(O)SCH,° FC(O)SCI,[12) FC(O)SBr,41 and CIC(O)SBr!' The unambiguous identification of IR absorptions due to the less stable anti rotamer allows us to conclude that the vapor is composed of approximately 98% of the syn form and 2% of the anti form at ambient temperatures, in good agreement with the forecasts of quantum chemical calculations. Both forms of FC(O)SCH3 then photodecompose. The main reaction channel involves the elimination of CO with the formation of the hitherto elusive sulfenyl fluoride CH3SF, thus emulating similar photochemical processes starting from CIC(O)SCH,,\") FC(O)SC1,3) FC(O)SBr,* and CIC(O)SBr.!']",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
